word_summaries_chapter_112:
  112:1:1:"The first word of verse (112:1) is an imperative verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل أمر</span>). The verb is second person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">qāf wāw lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ق و ل</span>)."
  112:1:2:"The second word of verse (112:1) is a third person masculine singular personal pronoun."
  112:1:3:"The third word of verse (112:1) is a proper noun in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The proper noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza lām hā</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ل ه</span>)."
  112:1:4:"The fourth word of verse (112:1) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza ḥā dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ح د</span>)."
  112:2:1:"The first word of verse (112:2) is a proper noun in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The proper noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza lām hā</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ل ه</span>)."
  112:2:2:"The second word of verse (112:2) is a masculine singular noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṣād mīm dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ص م د</span>)."
  112:3:1:"The first word of verse (112:3) is a negative particle."
  112:3:2:"The second word of verse (112:3) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw lām dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">و ل د</span>)."
  112:3:3:"The third word of verse (112:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and negative particle. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  112:3:4:"The fourth word of verse (112:3) is a passive imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw lām dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">و ل د</span>)."
  112:4:1:"The first word of verse (112:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and negative particle. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  112:4:2:"The second word of verse (112:4) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">kāf wāw nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ك و ن</span>). The verb (<span class=\"at\">يكن</span>) belongs to a special group of words known as <i class=\"ab\">kāna</i> and her sisters (<span class=\"at\">كان واخواتها</span>)."
  112:4:3:"The third word of verse (112:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and personal pronoun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"for\". The personal pronoun is third person masculine singular. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  112:4:4:"The fourth word of verse (112:4) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">kāf fā hamza</i> (<span class=\"at\">ك ف أ</span>)."
  112:4:5:"The fifth word of verse (112:4) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza ḥā dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ح د</span>)."